  "prompt": "Who is Roger Goodell? What was his role in the DeflateGate scandal?",
  "response": "Roger Goodell is the Commissioner of the National Football League (NFL) since 2006. In the DeflateGate scandal involving the New England Patriots and quarterback Tom Brady in 2015, Goodell played a central role in investigating and ultimately suspending Brady for four games.\n\nThe controversy arose after the AFC Championship game between the Patriots and Indianapolis Colts, where it was alleged that the Patriots deliberately underinflated footballs to gain a competitive advantage. As NFL Commissioner, Goodell commissioned an investigation led by Ted Wells, which concluded that it was \"more probable than not\" that Brady was aware of and approved of the ball deflation.\n\nGoodell subsequently suspended Brady for four games, which led to a lengthy legal battle. Brady challenged the suspension through federal court, and the case went through multiple legal proceedings. Eventually, after appeals and legal challenges, Brady served the four-game suspension at the start of the 2016 NFL season.\n\nGoodell's handling of the DeflateGate scandal was widely criticized, with some perceiving his actions as overly punitive and others seeing it as an example of his broader disciplinary powers as NFL Commissioner. The incident became a significant and contentious moment in NFL history and in Goodell's tenure as commissioner.",
